Ever wonder why the iPhone is so expensive? This might be the explanation👇

Apple employs a very unique business approach called the “reverse razor” and no, it doesn’t have anything to do with razors. 

It means that they price the hero product (like their iPhone) very high and make secondary products (like songs) very low. 

This contributed to their initial success when the iPhone was released back in 2007. 

The name “reverse razor” comes from the standard practices around selling razors. Companies typically make the razor cheap and the blade super expensive to generate profit. 

Can you think of other products that use a similar model? Drop it in the comments.

Will investing $100 every month till you’re 65 make you a millionaire? Debatable. Read👇

If you invest $100 per month you’d need a 13% annual return to retire as a millionaire by 65.

But the average annual market return is actually closer to 8-10%. 

So, the likelihood of you retiring by 65 only investing $100 is highly unlikely. 

What do you do if you want to retire a millionaire by 65?

Watch to see the video to see the amounts you’d really need to invest to be set up for retirement.

Berkshire Hathaway is one of the most expensive stocks in the world. Here’s why👇

Berkshire offers potential investors a Class A share and Class B share. 

You can own a Class A share for the hefty price tag of $654,000. This gives the holder much higher voting right weight and allows the investor to attend shareholder meetings.

Warren Buffet wanted to make sure anyone who originally invested in Berkshire Hathaway was high quality. Think of it as a vetting process for investors. 

The problem was… not a ton of investors could afford the stock. So, in the 90s Buffet opened up the Class B share option.

This option allows investors to still get a piece of the company but with reduced voting rights and share value. 

Which would you choose?

Gold prices are at all time highs but why? 🤔👇

Here are the biggest culprits behind the gold rush. 

#1 Gold is a sure thing. In times of uncertainty, people often flock to gold because of its longevity. It is, after all one, of the oldest forms of payment we have. 

#2 Central Banks. Central banks have been stockpiling gold. Their thirst for gold continues to boost demand and this drives up the prices.

#3 It’s an inflation risk hedge. Gold prices historically go up as inflation increases which means it’s a great way to combat against your reduced purchasing power (thanks inflation!)

Bi-weekly payments can actually reduce the amount of interest you owe on the life of a loan as well as the total term you need to pay it. That’s because with bi-weekly payments you are making one extra monthly payment throughout the course of a year - which lessens you overall loan burden, and thus, interest.

From Mortgage Retirement Professor:
“For example, the monthly payment on a $100,000 8% loan for 30 years is $733.77. On a biweekly payment plan, you’d pay half this amount every two weeks, or 26 payments over a year. This is the equivalent of one extra monthly payment — 13 instead of 12. You’d pay off your loan in 277 months, rather than 360 and save $44,160 in interest payments.”

Here are some options after you max out your IRA or Roth IRA 👇

1. 401k Match - Free Money that is from your employer. Some employers offer this perk and for every dollar you contribute, they match it to your 401k, up to a certain limit. If they offer this, make sure to take advantage of it.
2. Taxable brokerage account - you can open up an investing account at a big brokerage like Fidelity, Schwab, etc and invest after-tax dollars into index funds, individual stocks, bonds, etc. Make sure to keep it reasonable and within your risk profile
3. 529 and HSAs. Basically, other accounts that give you tax advantages with certain use cases.
